{"title_page": "Ravindra Kaushik", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ravindra Kaushik\n| image              = Ravinder Kaushik former RAW agent.jpg\n| alt                = Former RAW agent Ravi\n| caption            = Former RAW agent Ravindra Kaushik\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=yes|1952|04|11}}<ref name=\"toi\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Sri Ganganagar]], [[Rajasthan]], India]\n| death_date         = {{death year and age|1999|1952}}<ref name=\"tel\"/>\n| death_place        = [[Central Jail Mianwali]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan\n| nationality        = Indian\n| other_names        = Nabi Ahmed Shakir, \"Black Tiger\"\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Karachi]]\n| occupation         = [[Intelligence agent]] (India), [[Major in Pakistani Army]] (Pakistan)\n| years_active       = 1975&ndash;1983\n| employer           = {{unbulleted list|[[Research and Analysis Wing]]|[[Pakistan Army]]}}\n| known_for          = Indian spy for RAW\n| criminal_penalty   = [[Life imprisonment]]\n}}\n\n'''Ravindra Kaushik''' ({{aka}} '''Nabi Ahmed Shakir'''; 11 April 1952 \u2013 November 2001) was an alleged [[India]]n [[Research and Analysis Wing]] (RAW) agent who lived undercover in [[Pakistan]] before he was jailed and died.<ref name=\"tel\">{{cite web|title=India's forgotten spy \u2013 Agent's family fights an impossible battle |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1021230/asp/frontpage/story_1526967.asp|accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"dap\">{{cite web|title=Late spy's kin fight for reel life credit |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/nation/86994-late-spys-kin-fight-for-reel-life-credit.html |accessdate=17 August 2012 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824211533/http://www.dailypioneer.com/nation/86994-late-spys-kin-fight-for-reel-life-credit.html |archivedate=24 August 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1334049|title=A history of Indian spies in Pakistan|last=Osman|first=Ali|date=2017-05-19|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRavindra Kaushik was born in [[Sri Ganganagar]], [[Rajasthan]] on April 11, 1952. He also did his graduation from there.<ref name=\"toi\"/>\n\n==Research and Analysis Wing==\nKaushik displayed his talent at the national level dramatic meet in [[Lucknow]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], which was witnessed by officials from the [[Research and Analysis Wing]] (RAW), India's external intelligence agency. He was contacted and offered a job of being an [[undercover]] Indian agent in Pakistan. Kaushik was given extensive training in [[Delhi]] for two years. He underwent [[circumcision]] so he could pass as a [[Muslim]]. He was taught [[Urdu]], given Islamic religious education and acquainted with the topography and other details about Pakistan. Being from Sri Ganganagar, a city near Rajasthan's border with [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]], he was well versed in [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], which is widely understood in Punjab,Pakistan.<ref name=\"dap\" /> In 1975, at the age of 23, Kaushik was sent to Pakistan on a special mission.<ref name=\"tel\" /><ref name=\"toi\">{{cite web|title=Salman Khan's new movie in controversy again|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-24/jaipur/32827242_1_multan-pakistan-army-pakistan-agency|accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"ind\">{{cite web|title=Dead RAW agent's nephew takes Salman's Ek Tha Tiger producers to court|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/raw-agent-nephew-takes-salman-ek-tha-tiger-producers-court--4729.html|accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Activities in Pakistan==\nKaushik was given the name \"Nabi Ahmed Shakir\" and entered Pakistan in 1975.<ref name=\"dap\"/> He was successful in getting admission in [[University of Karachi|Karachi University]] and completed his [[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]]. He joined Pakistan Army as a commissioned officer and eventually promoted to the rank of a major.<ref name=\"hindustantimes\">https://m.economictimes.com/news/defence/story-of-raw-agent-ravinder-kaushik-who-worked-as-a-pakistan-army-major/-the-greatest-spy-of-india/slideshow/58240718.cms</ref> He soon married a local girl named Amanat, the daughter of a tailor in one of the army units, and fathered a boy who died in 2012\u20132013.<ref name=\"dap\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/jaipur/the-real-life-behind-a-2002-spy-thriller/article1-483474.aspx|title=The real life behind a 2002 spy thriller|work=Hindustan Times|date=6 December 2009|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1979 to 1983, while working as an officer, he passed on valuable information to [[Research and Analysis Wing|RAW]] which was of great help to the Indian defence forces. He was given the title of 'Black Tiger' by India's then home minister [[S. B. Chavan]].<ref name=\"one\">{{cite web|title=Ek Tha Tiger: Not Salman Khan, meet the real Indian Tiger! |url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/news/2012/ek-tha-tiger-salman-khan-real-tiger-ravinder-kaushik-098458.html|accessdate=17 Aug 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Death and aftermath==\nIn September 1983, Indian intelligence agencies sent a low-level operative, Inyat Masih, to get in touch with Kaushik. However, Masih was caught by Pakistan's intelligence agencies and revealed Kaushik's true identity.<ref name=\"tel\" /> Kaushik was then captured, tortured for two years at an interrogation center in [[Sialkot]]. He was given the death sentence in 1985. His sentence was later commuted to a life term by the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan]]. He was kept in various jails in various cities, including Sialkot, [[Kot Lakhpat]] and in [[Mianwali]] jail for 16 years.<ref name=\"dap\" /> He managed to secretly send letters to his family in India, which revealed his poor health condition and the trauma faced by him in Pakistani jails. In one of his letters he wrote:{{quote|Kya Bharat jaise bade desh ke liye kurbani dene waalon ko yahi milta hai?\" (Is this the reward a person gets for sacrificing his life for a great nation like India?)<ref name=\"tel\"/>}}\n\nIn November 2001, he succumbed to [[pulmonary tuberculosis]] and [[heart disease]] in [[Central Jail Mianwali]] in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan.<ref name=\"tel\" />\n\nAccording to Ravindra's family, [[Government of India|Indian government]] refused to recognise him and made no effort to help him.<ref name=\"tel\" />\n\nRavindra's family claimed that the storyline of the famous Bollywood flick \"[[Ek Tha Tiger]]\" released in the year 2012 was based on the life of Ravindra and asked for the credit in the movie titles for Ravindra.<ref name=\"ind\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sarabjit Singh]]\n*[[Kashmir Singh]]\n*[[Kulbhushan Jadhav]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book|author1=S Hussain Zaidi|author2=Brijesh Singh|title=Dangerous Minds: Eight Riveting Profiles of Homegrown Terrorists|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jbstDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT61|date=2018|publisher=[[Penguin Random House]]|isbn=978-93-86495-99-0|pages=61\u201363}}\n*{{cite web |author=Presley Thomas |title=The real life behind a 2002 spy thriller |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/jaipur/the-real-life-behind-a-2002-spy-thriller/story-U9NVg1hsRRh4vizo9fRxhN.html |website=[[Hindustan Times]] |language=en |date=6 December 2009}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaushik, Ravindra}}\n[[Category:Indian expatriates in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:India\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n[[Category:Indian people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Indian people who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:Indian spies]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Army officers]]\n[[Category:People of the Research and Analysis Wing]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in Pakistani detention]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:University of Karachi alumni]]\n[[Category:Spies who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:People convicted of espionage in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Research and Analysis Wing activities in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Tuberculosis deaths in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:21st-century deaths from tuberculosis]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ravindra Kaushik\n| image              = Ravinder Kaushik former RAW agent.jpg\n| alt                = Former RAW agent Ravi\n| caption            = Former RAW agent Ravindra Kaushik\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=yes|1952|04|11}}<ref name=\"toi\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Sri Ganganagar]], [[Rajasthan]], India]\n| death_date         = {{death year and age|1999|1952}}<ref name=\"tel\"/>\n| death_place        = [[Central Jail Mianwali]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan\n| nationality        = Indian\n| other_names        = Nabi Ahmed Shakir, \"Black Tiger\"\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Karachi]]\n| occupation         = [[Intelligence agent]] (India), [[Major in Pakistani Army]] (Pakistan)\n| years_active       = 1975&ndash;1983\n| employer           = {{unbulleted list|[[Research and Analysis Wing]]|[[Pakistan Army]]}}\n| known_for          = Indian spy for RAW\n| criminal_penalty   = [[Life imprisonment]]\n}}\n\n'''Ravindra Kaushik''' ({{aka}} '''Nabi Ahmed Shakir'''; 11 April 1952 \u2013 November 2001) was an alleged [[India]]n [[Research and Analysis Wing]] (RAW) agent who lived undercover in [[Pakistan]] before he was jailed and died.<ref name=\"tel\">{{cite web|title=India's forgotten spy \u2013 Agent's family fights an impossible battle |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1021230/asp/frontpage/story_1526967.asp|accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"dap\">{{cite web|title=Late spy's kin fight for reel life credit |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/nation/86994-late-spys-kin-fight-for-reel-life-credit.html |accessdate=17 August 2012 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824211533/http://www.dailypioneer.com/nation/86994-late-spys-kin-fight-for-reel-life-credit.html |archivedate=24 August 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1334049|title=A history of Indian spies in Pakistan|last=Osman|first=Ali|date=2017-05-19|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRavindra Kaushik was born in [[Sri Ganganagar]], [[Rajasthan]] on April 11, 1952. He also did his graduation from there.<ref name=\"toi\"/>\n\n==Research and Analysis Wing==\nKaushik displayed his talent at the national level dramatic meet in [[Lucknow]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], which was witnessed by officials from the [[Research and Analysis Wing]] (RAW), India's external intelligence agency. He was contacted and offered a job of being an [[undercover]] Indian agent in Pakistan. Kaushik was given extensive training in [[Delhi]] for two years. He underwent [[circumcision]] so he could pass as a [[Muslim]]. He was taught [[Urdu]], given Islamic religious education and acquainted with the topography and other details about Pakistan. Being from Sri Ganganagar, a city near Rajasthan's border with [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]], he was well versed in [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], which is widely understood in Punjab,Pakistan.<ref name=\"dap\" /> In 1975, at the age of 23, Kaushik was sent to Pakistan on a special mission.<ref name=\"tel\" /><ref name=\"toi\">{{cite web|title=Salman Khan's new movie in controversy again|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-24/jaipur/32827242_1_multan-pakistan-army-pakistan-agency|accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"ind\">{{cite web|title=Dead RAW agent's nephew takes Salman's Ek Tha Tiger producers to court|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/raw-agent-nephew-takes-salman-ek-tha-tiger-producers-court--4729.html|accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Activities in Pakistan==\nKaushik was given the name \"Nabi Ahmed Shakir\" and entered Pakistan in 1975.<ref name=\"dap\"/> He was successful in getting admission in [[University of Karachi|Karachi University]] and completed his [[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]]. He joined Pakistan Army as a commissioned officer and eventually promoted to the rank of a major.<ref name=\"hindustantimes\">https://m.economictimes.com/news/defence/story-of-raw-agent-ravinder-kaushik-who-worked-as-a-pakistan-army-major/-the-greatest-spy-of-india/slideshow/58240718.cms</ref> He soon married a local girl named Amanat, the daughter of a tailor in one of the army units, and fathered a boy who died in 2012\u20132013.<ref name=\"dap\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/jaipur/the-real-life-behind-a-2002-spy-thriller/article1-483474.aspx|title=The real life behind a 2002 spy thriller|work=Hindustan Times|date=6 December 2009|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1979 to 1983, while working as an officer, he passed on valuable information to [[Research and Analysis Wing|RAW]] which was of great help to the Indian defence forces. He was given the title of 'Black Tiger' by India's then home minister [[S. B. Chavan]].<ref name=\"one\">{{cite web|title=Ek Tha Tiger: Not Salman Khan, meet the real Indian Tiger! |url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/news/2012/ek-tha-tiger-salman-khan-real-tiger-ravinder-kaushik-098458.html|accessdate=17 Aug 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Death and aftermath==\nIn September 1983, Indian intelligence agencies sent a low-level operative, Inyat Masih, to get in touch with Kaushik. However, Masih was caught by Pakistan's intelligence agencies and revealed Kaushik's true identity.<ref name=\"tel\" /> Kaushik was then captured, tortured for two years at an interrogation center in [[Sialkot]]. He was given the death sentence in 1985. His sentence was later commuted to a life term by the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan]]. He was kept in various jails in various cities, including Sialkot, [[Kot Lakhpat]] and in [[Mianwali]] jail for 16 years.<ref name=\"dap\" /> He managed to secretly send letters to his family in India, which revealed his poor health condition and the trauma faced by him in Pakistani jails. In one of his letters he wrote:{{quote|Kya Bharat jaise bade desh ke liye kurbani dene waalon ko yahi milta hai?\" (Is this the reward a person gets for sacrificing his life for a great nation like India?)<ref name=\"tel\"/>}}\n\nIn November 2001, he succumbed to [[pulmonary tuberculosis]] and [[heart disease]] in [[Central Jail Mianwali]] in [[Punjab]], Pakistan.<ref name=\"tel\" />\n\nAccording to Ravindra's family, [[Government of India|Indian government]] refused to recognise him and made no effort to help him.<ref name=\"tel\" />\n\nRavindra's family claimed that the storyline of the famous Bollywood flick \"[[Ek Tha Tiger]]\" released in the year 2012 was based on the life of Ravindra and asked for the credit in the movie titles for Ravindra.<ref name=\"ind\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sarabjit Singh]]\n*[[Kashmir Singh]]\n*[[Kulbhushan Jadhav]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book|author1=S Hussain Zaidi|author2=Brijesh Singh|title=Dangerous Minds: Eight Riveting Profiles of Homegrown Terrorists|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jbstDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT61|date=2018|publisher=[[Penguin Random House]]|isbn=978-93-86495-99-0|pages=61\u201363}}\n*{{cite web |author=Presley Thomas |title=The real life behind a 2002 spy thriller |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/jaipur/the-real-life-behind-a-2002-spy-thriller/story-U9NVg1hsRRh4vizo9fRxhN.html |website=[[Hindustan Times]] |language=en |date=6 December 2009}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaushik, Ravindra}}\n[[Category:Indian expatriates in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:India\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n[[Category:Indian people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Indian people who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:Indian spies]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Army officers]]\n[[Category:People of th